g Function Properties**\n\nI\'m now detailing additional filter functions, starting with `IS_BETWEEN`. I\'ve added a Boolean check for strict value matching using `EQUALS` and the `IN_ARRAY` function. I\'m focusing on their parameters, signatures, and sample outputs, ensuring each is well-defined and easy to understand. I will ensure they are usable within the test sandbox.\n\n\n**Expanding Function Parameters**\n\nI\'m now detailing `IN_ARRAY` filter function parameters like \'target\' and \'list_values\' alongside the return type `BOOLEAN`. I\'m also reviewing `SUM` aggregate function with parameters for \'collection\' and \'field_name\', returning a `FLOAT`, and defining a sample output for clarity.\n\n\n**Defining Aggregates**\n\nI\'m now detailing an aggregate function for counting items, `COUNT`, which includes parameters for \'collection\' and an optional \'condition\' returning an integer. The `AVERAGE` function is being defined for calculations on a collection, \'field\', and \'window\', providing a float value. These parameters are essential for a robust aggregation design.\n\n\n**Defining Function Record Select**\n\nI\'m now detailing record selection functions. I\'ve defined `FIRST`, `LAST`, and `RANGE`, which all allow sorting. These will select a range of records from a collection based on a specified attribute, along with numeric limits or offsets. I\'ve designed the parameter structures to provide intuitive options. I\'m focusing on providing sample outputs for clarity.\n\n\n**Finalizing Record Selection**\n\nI\'ve finished defining all record selection functions, including `FIRST`, `LAST`, and `RANGE`, which cover sorting criteria. I\'ve designed their parameters for a collection, sorting attribute, and numeric limits. The parameter structures are perfect, and I have provided sample outputs for clarity.\n\n\n**Implementing Function Wizard**\n\nI\'m now implementing the function wizard UI flow with state management! I\'m creating the multi-step wizard component, leveraging states like `wizardStep`, `fxName`, and others to control the UI and user input. The states are matching the mockup exactly. I\'m focusing on dynamic step rendering and seamless navigation between the four stages, ensuring the UX will be flawless.\n\n\n**Refining Function Preview**\n\nI\'m now refining the dynamic preview calculations in the Function Builder! I\'m focusing on Step 4 and generating text like \"{aggregateOperation.toUpperCase()} of {aggregateField}\". I will also generate an output signature preview like `fn: {formattedName}() -> {returnType}` and also am now wondering how to format the names.\n\n\n\n**Formatting Function Names**\n\nI\'m now detailing the function naming convention! I\'ve decided to use `snake_case` for the function signature, like `total_high_value_txns`. I\'ve added a function to handle this for user-provided names, and it is a beautiful solution! I\'m also ensuring the correct return types, such as `Float` for `sum` and `avg` operations.\n\n\n**Implementing Function Component**\n\nI\'m now detailing a robust code structure for `/src/components/Functions.tsx`! I\'m focusing on a layout that is inspired by the mockup and a responsive sidebar, with grid cards for filter functions, a dense table for aggregates and grid cards for sorting & selection. The interactive multi-step builder and a dynamic playground/tester with compiler simulation are next. I\'m focusing on implementing an edit workflow for existing functions, which opens the Wizard pre-populated with function details, to support both custom and built-in functions. I will ensure that the edit workflow will be responsive and functional.\n\n\n\n**Implementing Function Editor**\n\nI\'m now detailing the implementation of the edit workflow within `/src/components/Functions.tsx`. I\'m starting from scratch with a well-defined state and component structure, including full replacement of `/src/components/Functions.tsx` with a new, updated version! I\'m focusing on seamless integration of the function wizard for both creating and editing functions.\n\n\n"
