    thinking: "**Celebrating Code Completion**\n\nMy initial pass is complete! The code compiles, lints, and functions flawlessly. Type safety is confirmed, it\'s cleanly structured, and the integration with the platform is smooth. I\'m pleased with the outcome; it feels like a significant stride forward.\n\n\n**Expanding Functionality Implementation**\n\nI\'ve greatly expanded the initial function set, now encompassing over nine functions across diverse categories: \"Filter Functions,\" \"Aggregates,\" and \"Record Selection & Sorting.\" I\'ve also integrated a stunning, intuitive live search and category chips filter, mirroring the mockups perfectly. Moreover, I\'ve implemented a comprehensive 4-step function builder wizard with full roundtrip editability, including deletion functionality and clean-up.\n\n\n"
    modified_response: "I have successfully added and deeply integrated the advanced **Functions Library** and interactive **Function Builder Wizard** modules into the Logic Engine application. \n\nHere is a summary of the polished features now live:\n\n### 1. **High-Fidelity Functions Library Layout**\n- **Category-Based Divisions**: Added structured sections for **Filter Functions**, **Aggregates**, and **Record Selection & Sorting** to browse active logical blocks.\n- **Dynamic Search & Filtering**: Implemented a real-time, fuzzy-search bar accompanied by category-specific filter chips (**All**, **Filter Functions**, **Aggregates**, **Record Selection & Sorting**) to instantly filter down the library.\n- **Adaptive Grid/Table Designs**: Built tailored presentation layouts (bento-grid cards for filters and sorting; a high-density, multi-column listing table for aggregate operations) that perfectly match the design specifications.\n\n### 2. **Multi-Step Function Builder Wizard**\nAccessible via the **\"+ Add Function\"** button, the builder guides authors through a cohesive 4-step logic compiler flow:\n- **Step 1: Source & Identification**: Set the logic cell name (e.g., `Total High Value Txns`), choose the database target collection (e.g., `Transactions`, `Users`), and document the business objective.\n- **Step 2: Filtering Specs**: Optionally toggle and configure custom criteria bounds (e.g., matching `amount > 1000` or `status == \"completed\"`).\n- **Step 3: Sorting & Selection**: Choose the sorting attribute (e.g., `transaction_timestamp`) with a toggle for **Ascending/Descending** and select the selection range bounds (**All Records**, **First N Records**, **Last N Records**, or **Index Range**) with dynamic parameter fields.\n- **Step 4: Mathematical Aggregation**: Choose from a grid of mathematical operations (**Sum**, **Average**, **Count**, **Min**, **Max**, **Rolling Average**) and map them to a target reducer field (e.g., `amount_usd`). \n- **Real-time Logic Summary & Signature**: Displays a dynamic, natural language logic compilation summary (e.g., *\"Takes the First 100 records from Transactions...\"*) alongside a clean signature generator (`fn: total_high_value_txns() -> Float`).\n\n### 3. **Integrated Sandbox Tester Console**\n- A live sidebar/panel allows users to instantly load any function, tweak raw parameter input vectors, and execute a compilation dry run.\n- Simulated pipeline executions print colorful compiler logs and real-time computation states directly inside the simulated **Compiler Sandbox Log** terminal preview.\n- Custom-authored functions can be re-edited or deleted directly from the active library.\n"
    thinking_duration {
      seconds: 1
      nanos: 768500823
    }
    stop_reason: STOP_REASON_STOP_PATTERN
  }
}
