    thinking: "**Analyzing Deployment Options**\n\nOkay, I\'ve got a grasp of the standard workspace files now. Crucially, I\'m examining deployment methods. It seems users have multiple sharing and exporting options, like Cloud Run or GitHub/ZIP. That\'s a key detail to integrate into this investigation of Google AI Studio Build.\n\n\n**Clarifying Access Restrictions**\n\nI\'ve confirmed that direct Git pushing isn\'t possible from this sandboxed Cloud Run environment. Because of security restrictions, I can\'t access GitHub credentials or authentication tokens. To export to GitHub, the user needs to use the **Settings/Export** menu within the AI Studio UI. I\'m preparing a clear explanation of this secure and supported workflow to avoid any confusion.\n\n\n"
    modified_response: "To push this application to your GitHub repository, you can use the built-in export features provided by Google AI Studio, as direct command-line authentication (SSH keys or Personal Access Tokens) to your private GitHub account is not available within this sandboxed workspace environment.\n\n### How to Export your Codebase to GitHub\n\n1. **Locate the Settings/Export Menu**: In the top-right corner of the **Google AI Studio Build** interface, click on the **Settings** gear icon or the **Export** menu button.\n2. **Choose Your Export Option**:\n   - **Export to GitHub**: Connect your GitHub account, select your target repository (`ashokraj2011/RuleUI`), and sync the files directly.\n   - **Download ZIP**: Alternatively, you can download the entire workspace as a `.zip` archive, extract it locally, and push it to your repository using your local Git client:\n     ```bash\n     git remote add origin https://github.com/ashokraj2011/RuleUI.git\n     git branch -M main\n     git add .\n     git commit -m \"Initial commit from AI Studio\"\n     git push -u origin main\n     ```\n\n### Code Status\nThe application is in a fully functional state:\n- All features (including the **Functions Library**, interactive **Wizard Builder**, and **Sandbox Tester**) are fully implemented.\n- The project has been verified and builds successfully (`npm run build`).\n- All files have been checked and passed ESLint/TypeScript verification (`npm run lint`)."
